questionRound.0.question.11.answer: The only color to watch is the far left. The far left color does not have anything to lose as its two highest values are in one row. Pick that row  and then pick the correlating row to the other colors until you get to yours.

See which color (person) has the best outcome. One person in the whole group has the best outcome if he/she chooses one obvious symbol  such as (30 or 40) if the person chooses XR and (10  15) if the person chooses YR. Thus  you track down to the color (person) who is to your left and see what that person will choose accordingly. The game becomes pretty simple once you can track down this strategy.

I just tried to figure out what my direct partner would pick to get the possibly highest score  and he would probably look at his other direct partner the same way I predicted him to do  and so forth.
One player  on the far right  always had an option which was better no matter what the other players picked.  Based on his decision  all the other players' decisions could be predicted.

My first object was to find the rule-setter (a.k.a. the person who had their 2 highest quantities in one horizontal row) since their choice would be obvious- the row with the two highest quantities in their grid is the way to go. Then I worked backwards to see what others would choose in accordance with the rule-setter's choice (in this case  I looked at vertical columns) until I got to my own grid. All the choices of the players with grids to the left of mine (i.e. not between me and the rule-setter) were irrelevant. In the case where I was the rule-setter  I made the obvious choice without consideration to anyone else's choices since they would be based on my own.

I would find the color that had either an x or y row that had the two highest values; based on that I would predict what the following color would choose (x or y) based on which row had the higher corresponding value. The rest of the predictions were made the same way.

I just hoped that the other people who matched with me  understood the concept that one of the color had only one option that would make sense as both the options for that choice were higher than the other two options. We were expected to work our way backwards to figure out what choice would be best suitable and present the most chance of sucess for us.

Find out the one who would definately choose X or Y ( for example  the biggest number in X role is still smaller than those in Y role  then there is high probability that this persone would choose Y)  and then predict reactions of other people.

During the first few parts  I haven't thought that much about what exactly strategies I could use during the game  but I know it is related to game theory. Accidentally  I recoginized the rules I could follow so that I could gain the most if I just follow the rule. It is a pretty interesting experiment since it helps people think about the biggest benefit of others and learn that in order to get more benefits for yourselves  you should learn about what others want first.

I would try to figure out all of the scenarios in which my slef and the teammates would try to coordinate in getting the right answers that would lead us in a overall high number from the choices that we were given. Eventually I would pick this up on and later realize that there were a number of sequences that would be able to occur if choosing the a choice that did not follow up with every one elses plan or vision.

Two general choices: Even exchange  where XR and YR have even value; OR One choice dominant: X>Y or Y>X.  | Dominant role should be the latter  since that person has no reason to choice the total smaller value choice over the larger one. In most cases  the even exchange roles have to comprimise for a slightly smaller value to get the greatest outcome due to the apparent decision by the dominant one.
Base my choices and assume everyone else bases their choices on the player who has one option that will give them the highest payoff regardless of the consequences
